Hi,
using python, I'm building a model that trains two LSTM. I tried to replicate the structure present in the sequence-to-sequence example for python, attention.py, found in the github directory. The problem is that when I use the SimpleSGDTrainer everything is okay, but with AdamTrainer the program fills the memory and the swap memory and gets automatically killed. This problem does not appear when I simply modify the code from attention.py using for example AdamTrainer.

The structure i have is:
SingleSampleTrain - a function that invokes the trainer, calls a function that generates the loss, does the backpropagation and updates the trainer;
GetLoss - it calls the embedder and then the encoder, applies  an activation function, gives an output in [0,1] and generates the loss;
Encoder - this one concatenate the samples representations, with some regularization, and gives them to the run_lstm function, identical to the one found in the example;
EmbedSequence - takes in input a list of vectors (of lenght 250) and creates a list of dy.Expressions of said vectors; I am not using a parameter collection for the embeddings (like in the example) because I don't want to update the values of the embeddings and each embedding represents a sentence, so they are not parameters usable both in training and testing.

In the attachment you can find the functions used in the training
[code.txt](https://github.com/clab/dynet/files/1859803/code.txt)

How can I solve the problem with the memory without using a lookup_parameter table?

